<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=101286784341057></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f101286784341057><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=13&mid=101286784341057>Cha vs Int and some other stats</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=13&mid=101286784341057#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=111700><span id=Scholar>dilenne</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>34 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Mon, Feb 4th 7:10 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[4.40]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Well, like some of you I created my enchanter before I ever heard of anyo of the sites like Allakhazam, but I'll throw my 2 cents in on what I've found out by level 37 about stats.&nbsp;&nbsp;Subject to change of opinion when I hit 54.  /grins.<br><br>Agnostic - I think I would have gone that way.  No benefit to following a deity.  LOTS of negatives if you do.<br><br>1.  STR-I put 5 points into STR on creation.  I think I should have put more.  I constantly have to carry stuff, or do because I can.  I get more loot and don't get enc. as much.  Mana regenerates slower when you're encumbered.  Just so you know, also if you are out of food and/or water.<br><br>2.  INT- overrated in many ways imho.  Too many items to count that add INT.  Yeah mana is good and yes we're oom a lot, cause we do a lot, not cause we don't have enough mana to start with.  Without major twinked items and Radiant Visage, (I've made, quested or bought everything I have) I have 153 int and 193 charisma.  <br><br>3.  CHA- Yeah, try charming a Hill giant with 120 Charisma and then try with 175+.  BIG difference.  The only thing here is Enchanters get CHA buffs and many of our quest items have Charisma in them too.  BUT, don't overlook putting a few points here.  Since getting my charisma to 193+ for group use, I've been much more successful in crowd control than before.  I can get it to 202 if I swap out my sapphire earrings, but have to give up strength to do it and have seen no apparent difference between charisma of 193 and 202.<br><br>3.  STA - I put a few into STA, that was a waste if you ask me.  You get 1hp per STA point.  Like that's going to save your life.  Rune gives you like 173 extra hp buffer, and Shields give more as well.  I think those points would have been better in INT, CHA or STR even.<br><br>Wouldn't bother with WIS, DEX, AGI either.  I swap out Polished Bone Bracelets with my Gold cats-eye bracelets when working on tradeskills, not sure if it really helps but it seems to, especially since I got gatorscale leggings.<br><br>Jewelcraft for fun and profit?  Well for fun, not for profit.  Unless you enjoy spending hours on end sending out auction's.  I'd rather be out fighting.  I'm at 185 skill in Jewelcraft and master of many others, cause I like the idea and I do it in my down time.  You won't make money at this unless your guild or sugar-daddy finances you, at least till after level 34, even then only at the expense of not questing, not fighting and not leveling.  shrugs your choice.  I enjoy the fact that I've made my gold sapphire earrings, most of my friends have good jewelry too.  But I'm just not in to sitting around auctioning stuff.  I can usually make more profit killing mobs.  You can usually buy the jewelry for much less than it will cost you to get to the skill level you'll need to make it yourself.  To me, it just makes a difference that I made it myself.<br><br>Other trade-skills to consider.  Well if you want some great items, the Coldain Prayer Shawl's look great to me.  You need Tailoring, Pottery (maybe), Brewing, and Baking.  All much cheaper to master than Jewel Craft, except the Tailoring.  I'd recommend taking up tailoring, you can make money sooner with HQ backpacks and it is required for the Coldain quests.<br><br>Soloing? Shrugs again. If I have to or if I'm bored, I can and do it pretty well most times.  Don't have to much since level 20.  Chanters pretty much rock in group and rarely have a problem getting a group if you want one.  Have played with charm soloing more since I got my charisma up, I rarely even load a nuke any more.  Make /pet attack hot key.  SoW nice, not always necessary, if no SoW make sure you know where the zone is and be close to it.  Have Nullify Magic and Color stun loaded, Beguile or charm pet after tash.  Pick your target (try different mobs in your zone, you'll figure out which ones work well), click on it hit /pet attack hot key.  Follow your pet and when you get close enough tash root the bad guy.  I don't root pet, my preference.  Watch health bars of both, if your pet is getting lower than the other, root pet, nullify magic, beguile the other one.  (You already tashed it before you rooted it so should be no problem).  Also if I have a pet and have had for a while, I re-charm before charm breaks if it hasn't withing one or two minutes and if mana is good, I don't know seems to work for me.  (note, you have been sitting or meditating during the fight right?) Other spells loaded depend on your preference etc.  I won't bore you with more details, play with it.  I tried charm at level 12, I don't recommend at that level solo.  With someone else backing you up, it's great practice.  Unless you're majorly twinked at level 12 your charisma is like 120, charm will usually break after about 20 seconds or so in my experience.  Hopefully the mob is dead by then, sometimes not.  (At level 12 you should try sirens; charm one have it attack the other.  Backup is good to have, make sure you have gate loaded though.)<br><br>Favorite things to charm.  Derv's, Kodiaks, Sarnaks.  It's so funny going to WC to kill bears for pelts and charm a Dervish Thug.  Lowbies will run up to him to try to attack as you run around looking for your next kill, thinking you're running away from him.  It's a riot.  You'll need a /rofl key for that one.  (side note, if you don't think your charisma makes a difference in charm time, try this charm a kodiak with no charisma buffs, sit around see how long it lasts, try with Charisma over 180 or so, I noticed a big difference.  Maybe it's just coincidence, but after I got my charisma to 193 I had an alligator following me for like half an hour in Cazic Thule.  Enchanter pets can be some of the most amusing in the game.)<br><br>Which brings up the next topic, Enchanter animations.   I use mine a lot more than many Enchanters at my level, I think.  I love my ani's.  They will protect me in weak groups who don't watch out for me, I can use them as support melee if we are caster heavy.  Need rune all the time for that.  I've even been main backup tank in a group with two enchanters.  Me and my little blender with dagger of dropping or bronze dagger with Augmentation can do a bunch of damage.<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
