<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=101500439326646></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f101500439326646><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=13&mid=101500439326646>Agro Management: Not Just a Melee Skill</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=13&mid=101500439326646#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=50451><span id=Scholar>riotgirl</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>54 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Mar 1st 12:40 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.33]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2><BLOCKQUOTE><b id=fs8>Quote:</b><hr size=1>Levels 16+ <br><br>first, land a sanity warp (or your best nuke) to pull. let it hit you as little as possible. have your pet take the blows while you land in DoTs and Nukes<hr size=1></BLOCKQUOTE><br><br>LOADING..PLEASE WAIT.<br>I offer you a cast-iron guarantee that you will not live long enough for your pet to be able to taunt the mob from your rotting corpse. It is not just the melee classes that have to grasp the concept of agro management.<br><br>Certain actions (esp. offensive actions) cause you to rise a certain amount on a mob's hate list. Sanity Warp (90+ DD spell) has a HUGE kicker for agro. Therefore, there are two immediate issues with this strategy:<br><br><b>(i)</b> At level 16, this spell is unreliable at best even with Tashan (Magic resistance debuff - should ALWAYS be your first or second spell. Improves your chance - and that of your group - to land spells). Without tashan, you're wasting mana and achieving HUGE taunt in the bargin. Bonus!<br><br><b>(ii)</b> It bears to reiterate that certain chanter spells have a high taunt factor. At level 19, I'm starting to take on board agro management and <i>timing</i> my spells - in the same way Wizards have to. Well, wizards that wish to remain healthy :P <br><br>The key to comedy, and agro management, is timing (from a caster's perspective). In a group situation, you land tashan, possibly wait for the tank to achieve taunt, and then follow up with other spells. Tip: Memory Blur is a fantastic spell to mop up hate (agro) when a mob is laying the beat down on your healer. Remarkable spell. In one of my groups, I noticed at the corner of my eye one of the mobs peel off from the group and beat down on the cleric. One liberal application of Mem Blur and said mob ignored the cleric (remember: turn OFF auto-attack - nothing worse then regaining agro) and retargetted the tank.<br><br>In a solo situation you most certainly do NOT land Sanity Warp as your first or even second spell. Massive, MASSIVE taunt which will cause your pet to intervene when the mob starts whopping your chanter ass (what with your whooping sub AC :P). Pet will not be able to taunt mob from beating down on you, which means you cannot mezmorise the mob due to pyschopathic pet .. unless you can stun, until (i) you can mem gate and beat feet, (ii) root the mob, or (iii) the pet manages to taunt the mob from you ..<br><br>I found out the HARD way against a crag spider. Hurts when a mob whacks you for 38 dam a pop, and its poison is absolutely <i>vile</i>. I got lucky. Root, fall back, let pet gain taunt. Was left with 1 1/2 bars of RED, 'tho. Exceedingly fortunate. <br><br>A better strategy adopted by many posters would be:<br><br><b>(i)</b> Lead with Tashan<br><b>(i)a</b> Attempt to Mezz target Mob if mob is 2.5 seconds distance from you (casting time) or ..<br><b>(ii)</b> Pet intervenes once the mob hits you, if so, back off<br><b>(iii)</b> DoT (Choke is a real goodie - debuff and a DoT)<br><b>(iv)</b> Depending on the specific mob, debuff .. e.g Languid Pace, Disempower, Weaken etc.<br><b>(v)</b> DD if necessary<br><br>My personal tactic is to rush into melee range and stun (colour flux - I will chain stun at lvl 20 by adding colour shift to a hotkey with flux. Mentioned elsewhere in this thread). 1 second casting time, minimal taunt, and best of all, your pet has 4 seconds worth of free attacks (not much, I grant you) but best of all, NO damage for those 4 seconds.<br><br>As has been stated, Chanters have a wide range of situational spells, and the ability to take down mobs to pissant size. That is the key soloing .. with our weak pets and their inherent disadvantage (no control) - adaptability. I like charm soloing for that adrenaline rush :P Caster madman make <i>excellent</i> pets - those spells can really lay the smack down. Have yet to try charming DBS [Dry Bones Skeletons] but would work equally as well in theory .. or unless, Charm breaks. c.f. stun.<br><br>**Note to self: Remember, and REMEMBER: colour flux (stun) is an AoE (Area of Effect) spell. It will affect ALL mobs in the spell radius - absolutely no discriminations. Not fun to have a kindly guard whack you for triple figures because it was caught in your stun.<br><br>To reiterate: when you hit level 16, you must start to grasp the concept of agro management. When your spells start to add a taunt kicker, and mobs start to hit in the high 30's +, apart from the healer, you are the class that cannot AFFORD to die. With your pitiful AC, you will not be able to withstand too many blows - better to learn agro management now than to rely on tanks regaining agro. ** When mobs start to whale in triple figures, you're usually dead at this point. Oh. And so is the party when their chanter dies.<br><br>Regards,<br>Riotgirl [Eliza Dushku Form] Hard Woman Enchanter<br>AyRo Server<br><br>&quot;she's like this cleavagey, slut-bomb walking around going 'oh, check me out. i'm wicked cool. i'm five by five'.&quot;<br><br><br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Fri Mar&nbsp;&nbsp;1 12:47:38 2002</em><br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
