<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=101215485031122></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f101215485031122><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=13&mid=101215485031122>Power Class</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=13&mid=101215485031122#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=139269><span id= >Jeek</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>5 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sun, Jan 27th 2:09 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[4.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Someone mentioned that Chanters are the most powerful class in game by far.&nbsp;&nbsp;I disagree though I love my enchanter dearly.  IMHO, Every class has a strong point and rule like anything in that area.  Clerics are just as powerful as enchanters, Necro's are one of the best soloer's besides Wizzies, and Druids.  Sk's and Necro's can get a corpse whereas the clerics cannot...Bards Can keep a group alive with similiar skills to those of enchanters provided they KNOW what to do.   <br><br>Anyhow, no class is really better than another but people just happen to enjoy playing one over another for some reason or another.  The big picture is that TEAMWORK and understanding how each class can serve each other is the key to success in the game.<br><br>I started off playing a cleric.  She is lvl 59 today.  My second character, I made an enchanter. As my cleric, I learned a lot about enchanters besides LOVING them.  For instance, I rune myself, I rune the cleric.  (btw, my enchanter is lvl 31 and tho twinked a little - she is definately not powerlvled.)  If there are more than one tank in the group, I explain that I will Alacrity them and I assign someone as my timer.  I have them use Ss to communicate that their speed has gone.  When that tanks is gone, so are the others going.  I have the monk tell me when to Aug him.  Sometimes, if I cannot find a good tank as a timer, I cast it on myself and time that way.  I know many players may want to say, why waste the time.  In a group, I once timed Alacrity on myself to use as the timer then kept it on the tank.  He didn't say much about it then but one week later, he told me, I SO LOVE YOUR SPEED!  <br><br>I will admit that it is annoying to have people break mezzes.  We, enchanters, often find that this occurs mostly with newbies.  I don't have much patience for dealing with that.  What I have done though is play my lvl 59 cleric and let others know that I have an alternate character who is an enchanter.  Lo and behold, so do they and before I know it...my enchanter gets an invitation to group with players who are alternates but just trying out another class.  Those are the best!  We really do find out how each class can benefit the other.  More so than that though, high lvls above 40ish Know not to break mezzes and have learned to /assist &lt;target tank&gt;, so when I play with their lower alternate character, BING!, no lessons need to be learned.<br><br>Newbies really need to listen up to higher lvls of their same class.  Oftentimes, I'll give a tell to a higher lvl'd enchanter that I admire with my cleric and I'll ask them for advice.  I am a professional at playing my cleric but I have much to learn with my enchanter.<br><br>One tip I was given that I found extremely effective as my enchanter was this:  Use F9 key, and targeting becomes much easier for mezzing.  Enthrall is better and last longers than Mezmerization; however there are instances AE mez comes in handy.  Stand Back when casting AE mez so that you do not mez yourself.<br><br>One last comment:  When I play my cleric, grouping with a bard AND enchanter is HEAVEN DIVINE!<br><br>Jeek<br><br><br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
