<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=101184495123014></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f101184495123014><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=13&mid=101184495123014>RE: help</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=13&mid=101184495123014#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=43653><span id=Scholar>GLASS</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>161 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, Jan 24th 12:03 AM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[3.70]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Hrmm, well about the only thing I can think to do is look at the level 12 spells and decide what I would have loaded now.&nbsp;&nbsp;This would be the setup I would use.<br><br>1)Tashan<br>2)Languid Pace<br>3)Chaotic Feedback<br>4)Mesmerize<br>5)Color Flux<br>6)Root<br>7)Choke (if grouped or animation soloing)  Charm (if charm soloing)<br>8)Rotating Buff Slot (Pet, Mist, Shielding, Strengthen)<br><br>If in a full group, I probably wouldn't cast much more than tash and slow on each mob, maybe a nuke here and there if I had plenty of mana.  If things started to get ugly, you would have your AoE stun, mez, and root loaded for crowd control.<br><br>If soloing with animation, I would start with tash and try to get a root off before the mob hit me.  This way the pet doesn't engage yet and he may actually survive the whole battle.  With the mob rooted I would slow and then DoT, maybe nuke until root breaks and then let the pet beat him the rest of the way to his death.<br><br>Charm soloing I never tried at this level, but if you have the cajones, then I would suggest trying it only if you have a SoW on at all times.  Even then I would have a hard time trusting this low level charm spell to stick long enough to be really effective.  But then, like I said, I never tried it myself.  Again I'd lead off with tash then try to charm my new buddy.  Once done, send him in against the target, tash the target, slow it, and maybe nuke once to turn the scale enough in your pet's favor.<br><br>This, looking back, is how I'd have my spells arranged if I was back at level 12.  Different people might have different ideas though, so this is by no means gospel truth.  The best you can probably do is goof around with each spell and decide if you like it or not.<br><br>have fun,<br><br>-Yizz<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
