<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=101173685120530></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f101173685120530><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=13&mid=101173685120530>Advice to new Enchanters.</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=13&mid=101173685120530#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=83141><span id=Scholar>Ellon the Charming</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>29 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Tue, Jan 22nd 6:01 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.23]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>1)&nbsp;&nbsp;If you want money, avoid tradeskills.  In today's game, trying to work on tradeskills early in your career will lead to poverty and much frustration.  I started jewelry at level 8, as soon as I got Enchant Silver, and to be quite honest, I'd have much better gear and much more money if I'd just left it alone and not have bothered with it.  I realize a lot of you are drawn to Enchanters just for jewelry.  If that's you, please stop playing an Enchanter.  You're going to end up spending more money on it than you will ever get back, unless you plan on spending a nice loooooooooong while in the FP area trying to peddle your wares (oh yeah, and you're only gonna make any sort of real money when you can start doing Platinum at level 34, and even then, good luck).<br><br>2) I don't advise trying to solo after level 5.  Just find groups.  You're gonna get a lot of people here who're gonna sell you on Charm-kiting, Mez-n-Nuke, AoE-Mez-n-Nuke, and a ton of other funky, gimmicky ways of trying to solo your Chanter, but my advice to you is just to stick to your guns and be the best grouping Enchanter you can be.  Enchanters are social by need and nature.  We control everything that's around us, and that gives us a ton of power.  However, we can't really do much in a void.  And for those who are going to argue that I probably just suck at soloing, I'm going to have to defend my credibility.  I did solo Noclin Saah in Paineel for about 2 levels.  I've also charm-kited Specs in Oasis (what a horribly fun time that was, watching newbies get slaughtered the first few times I tried it  :D ).  Sure, it was decent XP, but in a group, I would just command the puller to bring 3 or 4 mobs, and I'd keep them all in a nice, orderly line for my group to kill.  Oh...here are some numbers too:  In a group of 6, XP gets divided among 6 people rather evenly, throwing in a certain bonus percentage for having a full group.  Soloing, you may kill a mob once every 10 to 15 minutes.  In a group, you can kill 1 mob per 1 to 2 minutes, if your group is decent.  That means that in 15 minutes, you've just killed 5 or 6 mobs, and have gotten as much XP as you would've gotten soloing.  Plus, you just had the added advantage of being safe and secure AND you're ready to keep on pulling mobs, whereas if you were solo, you'd be on yer butt meditating.  :D  The bottom line is to just find groups.<br><br>3)  Learn your crowd control abilities early on.  No, Enchanters aren't &quot;defined as a class&quot; when they get to level 16 and get Breeze.  Breeze is 1 mana a tick, it's laughable.  The whole deal with Breeze-whore casters is that it's all in the mind.  They fool themselves into thinking that Breeze is some horribly powerful mana-regen spell.  It's 1 mana a tick, folks.  Nothing more.  Your mana is going to regen about 5 to 10 percent faster, that's about it.  But I digress.  You get Mesmerize at level 4 and Color Flux at level 8.  You're good to go.  Tell your pullers to start pulling in multiples.  Start teaching people how to assist each other.  Start working on tricks to target better (as you get older, you'll see that from levels 1 to 50, an Enchanter really just learns elaborate ways to click on targets).  Once you go beyond your greenhorn levels, you're ready to show people what a powerful class the Enchanter truly is.<br><br>4) Do research and teach others.  There are TONS of good guides out there for learning how to play an effective Enchanter.  Check out Allakhazam's links section, and I'm sure you'll find plenty of literature.  Go to those sites, explore, investigate, and when the time comes, show other people how to work with you, and learn to work with others (early in your career, it's going to be VERY difficult to get melee attackers to assist each other...they'll end up learnning as they go, trust me...yet, some still aren't smart enough to do so).<br><br>That's about all I've got for now...maybe one day, I'll write my own expansive &quot;How to be an Enchanter&quot; guide.<br><br>Oh...as a side note:  Please, do not refer to Clarity as &quot;crack&quot;, &quot;sugar&quot;, &quot;sweet thing&quot;, &quot;caster cocaine&quot;, &quot;Wizzie Dope&quot;, &quot;Cleric juice&quot; or any other silly name.  You defame Enchanters everywhere and make us vastly underrated in the eyes of other players.  We are Enchanters, be proud of that.  Without us, groups don't work.  (Oh, and when someone tells you that Bards can do our jobs, just laugh, leave their group and let them find a Bard...you're an Enchanter, you're elite, and nobody can do the job you do).<br>&nbsp;<br>Ellon Silktongue<br>54th level Illusionist<br>Drinal Server<br>Avengers of Honour</td></tr>
